description:
ChatGPT went down and people couldn't function. But the real problem goes much deeper than a service outage. From hikers getting lost after relying on ChatGPT to people uploading their entire closets for AI fashion advice, we are outsourcing every single thought to the LLM. Recent studies suggest we are losing our critical thinking and our ability to problem solve by over relying on ChatGPT. 

Research:
Microsoft: https://www.microsoft.com/en-us/research/wp-content/uploads/2025/01/lee_2025_ai_critical_thinking_survey.pdf

MIT: https://www.media.mit.edu/publications/your-brain-on-chatgpt/

Wharton: https://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=5104064

#ChatGPT

Chapters: 
00:00 Intro
00:43 Cannot Bake Without ChatGPT
01:50 ChatGPT Travel Information
02:30 Fact Checking NASA
03:33 Cheating in Interviews
04:32 Teachers: AI is Destroying Learning
05:40 AI and Calculator Comparison
05:56 ChatGPT and Universities
06:36 Cheating on Exam with AI
07:13 Relying on ChatGPT for Hiking
07:42 Leveling Up with ChatGPT
08:24 Wharton Research
08:50 MIT Research
09:25 Microsoft Research 
09:41 AI Paradox
10:24 Everyone Needs a Side Hustle
11:41 What Happened to Honing Your Craft?
12:23 AI Folks Discover “Thinking”
12:37 ChatGPT for Wardrobe

Am I getting older at an exponential rate?  We're now talking about how Googling things is better than asking AI.  
I'm from a time before the Internet.  We had to learn things and use critical thinking skills to figure out what we didn't know.  Looking something up meant opening a book, which might have meant going to a library and knowing how to use the card catalog just to find the books that might have what you want.  
When search engines came about, that was cheating at life and would make everyone dumb.  
Now the search engines are the better source of information we've chosen not to know in the first place.  And, the search engines are pushing to have us use AI features and summaries before we even see a legitimate expert source of info.

It's not just ChatGPT (but its the core of it). It's all the major players in the tech industry actively encouraging people NOT to think - to keep up with ChatGPT. When Adobe Acrobat tells me my lecture notes are long and asks if I want a summary. The lecture is 2.5 hours on Anatomy and Physiology - OF COURSE the notes are long! 
Gmail wants to summarize my emails with Gemini (I hate it, and it's usually wrong). I can't even create a document in MS Word or Excel without the little Co-Pilot image popping up anywhere my cursor is. 

I have students who don't even look at my study guides - they just drop them into ChatGPT and study the answers it gives them. 
Students who will take the Key Terms from the beginning of the chapter in their TEXTBOOKS and then put them into ChatGPT to learn the definitions. They don't even think enough to use the book they got the terms from. Like, even if you don't read the chapter, just go to the glossary and look the terms up. 

And even when I try to help them and tell them if they are going to use an AI tool, I suggest Notebook LM because you can upload the class materials (slides, notes, emailed resources) and it will create tools to study based on that material only - they will somehow rope ChatGPT into it.

comments.text:
Well, to be fair, people SHOULD use AI to cheat job interviews. Jobs use AI to screen you and sometimes even interview you with AI bots. It's not really "cheating" if you're just playing on the same level field as them. Let's be honest, jobs don't care about your "ability to answer questions" they want top-tier, polished, STAR format answers and likability. If you couldn't do the job, your resume would've already disqualified you. So... gaming them back the same way they game you is really just an even playing field IMO.

With regard to Googling - ChatGPT is far superior. Google shit the bed in 2017 and it's mostly just sponsored results now and AI itself. Of course, I say that with the IMPORTANT caveat that common sense should rule here. I mean, breaking down because ChatGPT is offline? bruh, yea you can just use Google, reddit, or youtube or ask somebody (like you said). But in the cake example, I'm sure ChatGPT's steps and breakdown would be on point with most YT'ers tutorials - just much faster and zero ads. Google would be a poor choice because it'd be sponsored crap and then click-baitey recipes chock full of cookies disclaimers and 23 popups with autoplay video ads. 

On the whole though, great video and I agree with you, just wanted to point those 2 things out
